%I A395943 #17 May 19 2026 16:10:20
%S A395943 1,0,2,14,184,16906,2442118,1435139134,2019636259814,7941042712515578
%N A395943 Number of tilings of an n X n grid by 1 X p rectangles using the prime partitions of n^2 into prime parts p <= n, counting distinct symmetry variants.
%C A395943 For each prime partition of n^2 into prime parts p <= n, tile an n X n grid using one 1 X p rectangle for each part p in the partition.
%C A395943 Rectangles may be placed horizontally or vertically.
%C A395943 Rotations and reflections of a tiling are counted when distinct.
%C A395943 A395942 counts the corresponding tilings up to rotation and reflection.
%C A395943 For n = 2..8, the ratio A395943(n)/A395942(n) increases toward 8.
%H A395943 Sean A. Irvine, <a href="https://github.com/archmageirvine/joeis/blob/master/src/irvine/oeis/a395/A395943.java">Java program</a> (github)
%H A395943 Chuck Seggelin, <a href="https://github.com/CSeggelin/SqTile">GitHub Repository containing source code used to compute the terms of A395941, A395942, and A395943, and a slide deck describing the technical challenges in the implementation.</a>
%e A395943 a(3) = 14 because there are 12 distinct symmetry variants of tilings of a 3 X 3 grid with three 1 X 2 rectangles and one 1 X 3 rectangle, and 2 distinct symmetry variants of tilings with three 1 X 3 rectangles. Thus 12 + 2 = 14.
%Y A395943 Cf. A000607, A254127, A395941, A395942.
%K A395943 nonn,more,new
%O A395943 0,3
